<div1 type="news" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head><orgName n="Richmond Dispatch" type="newspaper">Richmond Dispatch</orgName>.</head> 
<div2 type="morning" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head><date value="1862-07-22" authname="1862-07-22">Tuesday morning...July 22, 1862.</date></head> 
<div3 type="article" n="1" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head>Northern papers.</head> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="361" /> Our friends would greatly oblige us by sending any Northern papers they may chance to get in their possession to this office.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="362" />The public will thus receive the news at the earliest moment. </p> </div3> 
<div3 type="article" n="2" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head>Triumph of Abolitionism.</head> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="363" /> We need no better sign of the complete triumph of Abolitionism in the <rs>Northern Government</rs> than the shifting of sail by the <orgName n="New York Herald" type="newspaper">New York <hi rend="italics">Herald</hi></orgName>, which, from having been the bitter denouncer of the <name>Abolitionists</name> and their councils, charging upon them and their confiscation schemes the prolongation of the war, now gives in its approval of the measure for abolishing slavery, with compensation, as just and proper.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="364" />It goes further and acquiesces in the evident ultimatum of <persName n="Lincoln,,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00240" reg="mostcommon:Lincoln,nomatch:0" authname="lincoln"><surname full="yes">Lincoln</surname></persName>, that if abolition with compensation is rejected, then there must be abolition without it. It speaks of an interview between delegates in Congress from the border States and the <rs>President</rs> on this subject and the confiscation hill.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="365" />The <hi rend="italics">Herald</hi> declares that the <rs>President</rs> yielded nothing to their remonstrances, but pointed out to them the strait to which the border States were reduced, intimating that they had better come down gracefully and get pay. The delegates are represented to have gone off to consider the matter, and the <hi rend="italics">Herald</hi> infers that they are not likely to quarrel with their <q direct="unspecified">"bread and butter"</q>--in other words that they will not prove rebellious, and that they will go home and advise their constituents to fall down and worship the <rs>Washington Juggernaut</rs> while the wheels of his tyranny grind them into dust. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="366" /> There is nothing in the recent uncontrolled and uncontrollable away of the <name>Abolitionists</name> at the <rs>North</rs> to alarm the <rs>South</rs>.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="367" />Since the war began it has been virtually <num value="1">one</num> of robbery.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="368" />The daily journals <name>North</name> and <name>South</name> have furnished the daily evidence of this.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="369" />The Federal invaders have never spared the property of the <rs>Southern</rs> people.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="370" />The slaves were always taken when they could be transported, or when they could be induced to leave their homes.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="371" />None of them have ever been returned.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="372" />All other property has been appropriated to the uses of the <rs>Yankees</rs> wherever they have gone.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="373" />None but those traitors who took the oath of allegiance to the <rs>North</rs> were allowed to retain anything that <name>Yankee</name> cupidity or appetite, or <name>Yankee</name> malignity, desired to possess or wished to destroy.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="374" />The pretended respect for the rights of property which <persName n="Lincoln,,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00241" reg="mostcommon:Lincoln,nomatch:0" authname="lincoln"><surname full="yes">Lincoln</surname></persName> occasionally puts on — his reproof of <persName n="Hunter,,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00242" reg="mostcommon:Hunter,nomatch:0" authname="hunter"><surname full="yes">Hunter</surname></persName> and others — were all the most unscrupulous frauds.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="375" />He and his Government had from the beginning inaugurated and maintained the principles of <persName n="Hunter,,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00243" reg="mostcommon:Hunter,nomatch:0" authname="hunter"><surname full="yes">Hunter</surname></persName>'s order.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="376" />They denied the right of slave property to Southern men — they ordered it to be taken and not to be returned. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="377" /> The South gains by the open avowal of the policy somewhat insidiously pursued heretofore.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="378" />It is better that the <rs>South</rs> and the world should fully understand the policy of the <rs>Lincoln Government</rs>.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="379" />As a sequel to the last bold step, they have only to pass the measure enlisting and arming the slaves, to complete their new system of crushing the rebellion.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="380" />It is all the better that the world should know the real nature of the crusade against the <rs>South</rs> and the real temper of that brutal nation which will stop at nothing, however monstrous and barbarous, which they think can aid them in their war to subjugate the <rs>South</rs>.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="381" />The South has been satisfied all along that their enemies would go the full length of the most inhuman suggestion of their diabolical malignity.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="382" />It is gratifying to us that they have the boldness, or rather the madness, to avow their purpose. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="383" /> The South defies them, as it has from the beginning and will to the bitter end. The people of the <rs>South</rs> know that there is neither reason nor humanity at the <rs>North</rs>--that they can only protect their rights from insatiable rapacity and the most malignant destructiveness by their own courage and constancy.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="384" />They have no hope but this.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="385" />The world will doubtless be amazed and horrified at the barbarity of our invaders; but our strong arms alone can protect us from them.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="386" />Their nation is doomed to defeat, and yet to stand before the world the convicted felon — the detected thief, foiled in an attempt which might have borrowed some dignity from success. </p> </div3> 
<div3 type="article" n="3" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head>Fierce words.</head> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="387" /> The Yankee press talks and threatens as fiercely as ever, and their Congress adopts the most ferocious and inhuman measures.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="388" />They tell us they have hitherto treated us with humanity, but that hence-forth they shall handle us with gloves off. Confiscation, hanging, organized <placeName key="tgn,7001242" n="1.000 10" reg="Africa," authname="tgn,7001242">African</placeName> insurrection, are to be our future portion.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="389" />We are used to their truculent talk.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="390" />They must not suppose, because it is not retorted in kind, that the silence of the <rs>South</rs> arises from any other emotion than contempt.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="391" />We cannot bandy words with these animals, whose bark is worse than their bite.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="392" />When they put in execution some of their present inhuman threats, the <rs>South</rs> will reply, by taking an eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="393" />Woe to these demons when they unfurl their <q direct="unspecified">"death's head and cross bones,"</q> in anything but figures of speech! </p> </div3> </div2> </div1> 
